Patch Set 1:

Wondering if sticky sessions (as discussed in the bug report) would provide better load balancing?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Wondering if sticky sessions (as discussed in the bug report) would provide better load balancing?

That was my initial thought as well. Just had this patch already, so I thought I'd submit it as is.

One issue is that I don't think it is possible to use a session cookie with alertmanager and John mentioned that this can cause alerts to fire spuriously. With grafana we would need to whitelist the cookie so that grafana passes it through (grafana is acting as a proxy). The cookie would be stored in the clients browser. You can add the cookie to a whitelist when configuring the datasource.

If we used server affinity we wouldn't load balance the clients over the prometheus instances as the source IP would be grafana and not the client as it is acting as a proxy.

Just basing this off a quick skim of: https://www.haproxy.com/blog/load-balancing-affinity-persistence-sticky-sessions-what-you-need-to-know/

Of course I might have missed something. If anyone has some suggestions, I would be very happy to hear them :)

Patch Set 1: Backport-Candidate+1 Code-Review+1

I don't think session sticky is better here, even if it worked. We really want all operators to see the same version of the graph. The eaiest fix is to send everyone to the same prometheus.

Alert manager will still be getting alerts from all three promethus servers, and will continue to de-dupe those as normal. So the gain is we have a back up should the active node fail, and we have to loose all three controllers before we loose all ability to alert on problems.

But you are right, the trade off is not spreading the query load. Although if there is significant query load lissues, we probably want a caching proxying like trickster in the mix, rather than load balancing, for the same reasons as above.

... but I would say that, I wrote the first version of this, just sharing my thinking, in the hope we find a solution here.

Patch Set 2:

Hi Will, I just checked the OIDC WSGI documentation (1#https://github.com/zmartzone/mod_auth_openidc/wiki/Authorization#3-access-to-different-url-paths-on-a-per-provider-basis) and, in theory, it should work for multiple IdPs just selecting them in the Horizon dropdown menu on the login page.

Why it should work in theory?

Well, this property was initially developed to allow users to have custom discovery pages, that will receive some parameters from WSGI as described here (2#https://github.com/zmartzone/mod_auth_openidc/wiki/Multiple-Providers#discovery) and will send them to the configured custom discovery page, then the page should do the magic (allow the user to select one valid IdP) and redirect the user again to the "/redirect" endpoint with the initial parameters sent by the WSGI (described in 1#) and also the parameter "iss" that will be the Identity Provider selected.

So... if instead of configuring a custom discovery page URL, we simply configure directly the redirect URL with the "iss" that we want to use (that is what you did), it should do the trick to skip the discovery page and going directly to the Identity Provider authentication page, at least, in theory.

I did not test this one, but for me, there is no apparent reason to not work, maybe I am missing something, so if you could test this case, it should be very nice :)

Thanks!

Patch Set 7:

This is not required by bifrost kolla image,there are no call for the upper constraints on our kolla Dockerfile.

The issue you're linking is from bifrost team not kolla.
If you want to use the upper constraints within your bifrost container you can leverage the bifrost header block:

```
{% block bifrost_base_header %}{% endblock %}
```

and your template-override to inject your upper constraint customization without impacting the whole kolla community.

Cheers.
